<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO ARTHUR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb  5 14:52:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art<br>
The absurd allegation that everyone who entered the sevice in those years &quot;gave in to authoritarianism&quot; is nothing more than attempt for some to set themselves above those who did serve for whatever reasons. I truely don't care what that reason is. To assume that those who protested, versus those who served, hold the moral high ground is ludicrous. It is becoming apparent to me, through this site, that there are some who protested the war and those that went, have a hard time swallowing the idea that, the nation on the whole, have been trying to make amends to the Vietnam veteran for the wrongs inflicted on the vets for these many past years. I have yet to read from any protestors admitting that they, indeed, did &quot;spit&quot; on any vet, in any way, shape, or form.  I have even read calls for a Wall of their own.  How refreshing it would be to hear someone admit that they DID engage in those activities and explain the mindset at the time, instead of either justifying the behavior or denying it.  I would have much more respect for that individual rather than for the ones who insist that these things never occurred.<br><br>
Regarding your &quot;indoctrination&quot;.  My own father was a severely wounded WWII vet.  My only uncle, my fathers' younger brother, served in Korea.  Though I didn't know my grandparents, I knew that both my grandfathers served in WWI.  None that I knew who served in war, ever, related their experiences to me.  However, because of the little that I did know, I grew up with the idea that each generation had their own war and when I received my orders for Nam, it was just my turn and that was my war just as WWII was my fathers' war.<br><br>
As far as my reasons for entering the service, I explained all of that in &quot;Response to Nurse Ratchet&quot; on this thread.  It is my opinion that many who did protest the war did so because, in their locale, be it a university or whereever, that it was the &quot;in&quot; thing to do.  I have no doubt that many did so as a matter of conscience, but, as some accuse us of doing, some were sheep following the crowd, giving in to the &quot;authoritarianism&quot; of those campus protest leaders or their peers.<br><br>
As you have indicated, there are varied reasons why many went to Nam.  They are as as varied as those who went.  It is my understanding that there are vets who went because the judicial system (courts) gave some a choice of military service or jail although, if true, I suspect this was very rare.<br><br>
What path would I have taken if there were no Vietnam war?  I had spend considerable time thinking about this since reading your posting.  At the time, and due to circumstances, the military offered myself a way out and the only VIABLE alternative at that time of my life.  With the lack of resources available to me at the time, I still would have had no other options other than the military service.
